                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d671">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/5397: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-10-27T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 27, 1930—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>368. Department’s instruction 216, August 15.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>The Department has received a letter from the bank in question<note n="58"
                            xml:id="d671fn58">Not printed.</note> transmitting newspaper report that
                        the Chinese Government has asked foreign ministers to send representatives
                        to Nanking to discuss action in connection with defaulted obligations. The
                        bank indicates its willingness to consider sending a representative if the
                        American Minister should think this desirable.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Please report by telegraph whether note has been despatched in accordance
                        with Department’s instruction of August 15 and add comments on subjects
                        mentioned above.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
